 for bestpractices and # User Authentication

## Overview
Implement a secure, scalable user authentication system for StudySpark that supports sign-up, login, and logout using email/password and social OAuth providers (Google, Apple, Facebook). The system should provide JWT-based sessions with refresh tokens stored in secure HTTP-only cookies, strong password hashing, email verification, rate limiting, brute-force protection, and audit logging of security-relevant actions. The feature must integrate with existing project pages (page_p002, page_p003, page_p004, page_p020) and align with the StudySpark design system and accessibility goals.

## Components to Build
- User Data Model and Persistence
  - Users table with authentication fields, OAuth identifiers, verification status, and audit fields.
- Authentication Service
  - Sign-up (email/password) with password strength validation, hashing, and email verification token generation.
  - Sign-in (email/password) with login attempt tracking and rate limiting.
  - OAuth integration adapters for Google, Apple, Facebook with account linking.
  - Session management: issue JWT access tokens and refresh tokens; store refresh tokens in HTTP-only Secure cookies.
  - Sign-out: clear cookies and tokens, revoke sessions if needed.
- Email Verification & Transactional Email
  - Verification email sending via transactional email API; token validation endpoint; resend flow with rate limits.
- Password Management
  - Password hashing using bcrypt or argon2; password strength validation; password reset workflow (optional but recommended).
- Brute-Force Protection & Rate Limiting
  - IP and user-based rate limits, exponential backoff, temporary suspension for repeated failures.
- Audit Logging
  - Centralized, immutable logging for login, signup, password changes, OAuth events, token refresh, and sign-out.
- Security & Compliance
  - CSRF protection for state-changing endpoints, SameSite cookies, token rotation, secure cookie flags, and proper data handling per privacy requirements.
- Frontend Integration
  - UI screens and components for sign-up, login, account linking, password reset, email verification status, and sign-out flows.
- API Layer
  - Backend endpoints for authentication flows, OAuth callbacks, token refresh, email verification, and account management.
- Tests
  - Unit tests for core utilities (hashing, token generation/validation).
  - Integration tests for authentication flows.
  - E2E tests for sign-up, login, OAuth, email verification, and logout.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Pages/Views
  - SignUp page: email, password fields with strength meter, password visibility toggle, terms/consent, sign-up submit.
  - SignIn page: email, password, remember me, forgot password link, OAuth buttons for Google, Apple, Facebook.
  - Email Verification screen: indicate status, provide verification link guidance.
  - OAuth Connect/Link screen: link existing account to Google/Apple/Facebook.
  - Account dashboard: show login status, active sessions, and option to log out of other devices.
  - Password Reset flow (optional but recommended): request reset, set new password.
- Components
  - Input fields with accessible labels and validation feedback.
  - Password strength meter with real-time validation.
  - OAuth provider buttons with loading and success states.
  - Secure cookie-aware session indicators and token refresh handling.
  - Toasts/snackbars for success/error messages.
- State Management
  - Use React Context or a dedicated auth store to manage authentication state.
  - Initialize with an empty array-based or object-based state where appropriate (e.g., useState<User[]>([]) for lists, useState<AuthState>({ ... })). Follow runtime safety: initialize arrays with [] and guard against null data.
- API Interaction
  - Safely handle API responses: always validate shapes, e.g., const data = response?.data ?? []; then ensure Array.isArray(data) before mapping.
  - Implement fetch wrappers with proper error handling and null/undefined guards (e.g., const payload = req?.body ?? {}).
- Security & Accessibility
  - Ensure forms have aria attributes, proper focus management, and keyboard accessibility.
  - Store tokens in HTTP-only cookies; avoid exposing tokens in localStorage.
- Routing
  - Protect routes with authentication guards; redirect unauthenticated users from page_p002, page_p003, page_p004, page_p020 as needed.
- Testing
  - Add UI tests for sign-up and sign-in flows, including validation messages and OAuth initiations.
  - Mock API responses ensuring null-safe handling with data ?? [].
- Performance
  - Debounce login attempt validations and ensure no unnecessary re-renders.

### Backend
- Data Models
  - Users: id (uuid), email (unique), passwordHash, passwordSalt, isEmailVerified (bool), emailVerificationToken, oauthProviders (map/provider IDs), createdAt, updatedAt, lastLoginAt, failedLoginAttempts, accountLockedUntil.
  - Sessions/RefreshTokens: id, userId, tokenHash, expiresAt, createdAt, deviceInfo, ipAddress, isRevoked.
  - AuditLogs: id, userId, action, success, ipAddress, timestamp, metadata (JSON).
- API Endpoints
  - POST /auth/signup
    - Body: { email, password, fullName, tenant? } 
    - Actions: validate input, enforce password strength, hash password, create user, generate email verification token, send verification email.
  - POST /auth/login
    - Body: { email, password }
    - Actions: verify user, enforce rate limits, compare password, issue access token and refresh token cookies, update lastLoginAt, log audit.
  - POST /auth/logout
    - Clears cookies, revokes refresh tokens, logs audit.
  - POST /auth/refresh
    - Reads refresh token from httpOnly cookie, validates, rotates tokens, issues new access/refresh tokens.
  - GET /auth/verify-email?token=...
    - Validates token, marks user as verified.
  - POST /auth/resend-verification
    - Resends verification email with rate limits.
  - OAuth Endpoints
    - GET /auth/oauth/{provider}
      - Initiates OAuth flow (redirect to provider with appropriate scopes).
    - GET /auth/oauth/{provider}/callback
      - Handles provider callback, creates/link accounts, issues tokens, logs audit.
  - Password Reset (optional)
    - POST /auth/password-reset-request
    - POST /auth/password-reset
- Security
  - JWT signing with HS256/RS256 (depending on infra) and rotation policies.
  - Secure HTTP-only cookies for refresh tokens; SameSite=strict or lax as appropriate.
  - Password hashing with bcrypt or argon2; enforce strength checks server-side.
  - Brute-force protection: per-IP and per-user rate limits; temporary blocks after successive failures.
  - OAuth state validation to prevent CSRF.
  - Audit logs for login, signup, token refresh, logout, password changes, and OAuth events.
- Database Access
  - Use parameterized queries; guard against null results by defaulting to safe values.
  - Supabase-like patterns: data ?? [] when querying multiple rows; Array.isArray checks before map.
- Email & Notifications
  - Integrate with transactional email provider for verification and password reset notifications.
- Testing
  - Unit tests for hashing, token generation/verification, and edge cases.
  - Integration tests for signup/login/logout/refresh flows, email verification, and OAuth linking.
  - Security tests for rate limiting and token rotation.

### Integration
- Frontend-Backend Protocols
  - Stateless JWT access tokens; refresh tokens stored in secure cookies; token refresh flow via /auth/refresh.
  - OAuth providers redirect back to backend callback endpoints which then issue app tokens and redirect to authenticated frontend routes.
- Data Consistency
  - Ensure user identity is consistent across email/password and OAuth sign-ins; support account linking and conflict resolution.
- Shared Validation
  - Centralized validation utilities for email format, password strength, and username constraints; reuse across signup/login flows.
- Error Handling
  - Standardized error payloads with actionable messages for UI; avoid leaking sensitive information.

## User Experience Flow
1. User lands on the app with a greeting and a clear sign-in/up option (page_p002 or page_p003).
2. Sign-up
   - User enters email, password (with strength feedback), and optional full name.
   - Client validates input; on submit, server hashes password, creates user, and sends a verification email.
   - User receives email; clicks verification link; frontend confirms verification and prompts to sign in.
3. Sign-in
   - User enters email/password or chooses an OAuth provider (Google, Apple, Facebook).
   - If using email/password, server validates credentials, checks email verification status, issues access/refresh tokens, and redirects to the app dashboard (page_p004).
   - If OAuth, user consents, provider returns an identity; backend creates or links account, issues tokens, and navigates to app.
4. Session Management
   - Access token used for API calls; refresh token in an HTTP-only cookie triggers silent refresh as needed.
   - User can view active sessions in account dashboard and sign out from specific devices (sign-out flows).
5. Email Verification
   - If email not verified, UI shows status and a button to resend verification email with rate-limiting feedback.
6. Security & Recovery
   - If password lost, user can request password reset; transactional email sent; user resets password via secure link.
7. Audit & Compliance
   - All login/signup/OAuth actions are logged; admins can review security-relevant events.

## Technical Specifications
- Data Models: 
  - Users: id UUID, email string (unique), passwordHash string, isEmailVerified boolean, emailVerificationToken string, oauthProviders JSONB, createdAt timestamp, updatedAt timestamp, lastLoginAt timestamp, failedLoginAttempts int, accountLockedUntil timestamp.
  - RefreshTokens: id UUID, userId UUID, tokenHash string, expiresAt timestamp, createdAt timestamp, deviceInfo JSON, ipAddress string, isRevoked boolean.
  - AuditLogs: id UUID, userId UUID (nullable), action string, success boolean, ipAddress string, timestamp timestamp, metadata JSONB.
- API Endpoints: As listed above with methods POST/GET, appropriate path parameters, and query strings for tokens.
- Security: 
  - JWT-based sessions with short-lived access tokens and longer-lived refresh tokens.
  - bcrypt or argon2 for password hashing; implement salt management and pepper if policy requires.
  - OAuth 2.0 flows for Google, Apple, Facebook with PKCE where applicable.
  - Rate limiting per IP/user, brute-force protection, and account lockout after N failed attempts.
  - Email verification, secure cookie handling, CSRF protections, and audit logging.
- Validation:
  - Email format validation; password strength requirements (length, complexity, common password checks).
  - Validate OAuth provider data; ensure account linking integrity.
  - Use Optional chaining and safe defaults for all API responses; shapes validated server-side and client-side.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Sign-up creates a user, hashes password, and sends a verification email; user cannot sign in until email is verified.
- [ ] Sign-in with email/password issues access and refresh tokens; cookies are httpOnly, Secure, SameSite appropriately set.
- [ ] OAuth sign-in successfully creates or links a user account and issues tokens; supports Google, Apple, Facebook with proper PKCE/redirect handling.
- [ ] Token refresh endpoint rotates tokens, invalidates old tokens, and maintains data integrity; brute-force protections trigger after threshold.
- [ ] Email verification flow completes via token endpoint; resending verification is rate-limited.
- [ ] Audit logs record login, signup, password reset, OAuth events, token refresh, and sign-outs with accurate metadata.
- [ ] Frontend UI conforms to accessibility guidelines, responds to loading/error states, and handles null data safely using data ?? [] and Array.isArray checks.
- [ ] All API responses are validated; use safe defaults for missing data (e.g., const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []).
- [ ] No runtime crashes due to null/undefined values when using array methods; all arrays initialized as [] or guarded with (items ?? []).map(...) patterns.

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system and visual style:
- Use the provided color palette and typography guidelines to create cohesive sign-in/up screens.
- Card-based, rounded UI with soft shadows and pastel gradients for forms and prompts.
- Clear, friendly micro-interactions, with accessible controls and visual feedback for success/failure.
- Bottom navigation and top section elements should reflect the StudySpark aesthetic, ensuring consistency with page_p002, page_p003, page_p004, and page_p020.
- Ensure responsive layouts for mobile and desktop; maintain generous white space and comfortable tap targets.

